The Phoenix Suns will win the 2021 NBA Championship. While they finished the regular season with a better record than their Finals opponent (the Milwaukee Bucks), advanced stats portray the Suns and Bucks as similarly strong teams. In the postseason thus far, the Suns have a slightly better net rating, but postseason stats have a smaller sample-size and are largely matchup-based. The two regular season games in which the teams matched up were determined by 1-point margins, so the results of those games are inconclusive. I believe the Suns will win however, because of their dominance throughout this postseason relative to the Bucks. The Suns comfortably defeated both the Lakers and Nuggets, and struggled slightly against the Clippers, while the Bucks only comfortably swept the Heat, having major issues against the Nets and Hawks. The Bucks have various exploitable weaknesses, including Giannis Antetokounmpo's current injury and inability to shoot the ball well, Mike Budenholzer controversial coaching decisions and lack of adjustments, and the Bucks' overreliance on 3-point shooting. The Suns have the ability to score more efficiently at the rim, in the midrange, from the free-throw line, and only slightly less efficient from beyond the arc. The Bucks have no answer for Deandre Ayton, who is having the most efficient scoring postseason of all time, and can conversely defend Giannis better than any other defender in the league (per NBA.com). Chris Paul, Devin Booker, Mikal Bridges, Jae Crowder, Cameron Payne, Cameron Johnson, and Torrey Craig can provide efficient offense and lockdown defense for Phoenix, whereas Milwaukee lacks the depth to square off with them. Jrue Holiday and Khris Middleton can provide star support for Giannis, P.J. Tucker can provide good defense and corner shooting, and Bobby Portis Jr. can have his way against the Suns bench lineup, but they simply aren't equipped to deal with the resilient Suns team. Additionally, Monty Williams was a frontrunner for Coach of the Year this season, and has made quality adjustments in every series, and his superior coaching along with Chris Paul's superior leadership will let this Suns team win the series in 5 or 6 games.
Phoenix is rising.

Repeat championships are hard, ask any defending champion team in the NBA. However, LeBron James has been there and done it before. He's playing like an MVP once again and he's got a better supporting cast this year round. Injuries happen and Anthony Davis has picked up a recent calf strain that could create cause for concern, but we're a ways out from the playoffs. There are lots of other teams out there who are vying for the championship this year though. Philly and Utah are looking strong during the regular season, but neither of these squads have shown they have what it takes as players, or as established teams to win when the pressure is on in the playoffs. When picking "another team" you're also banking on the fact you have 26 other teams out of a pool of 30 (realistically there's only 6ish contenders). The Nets look frisky and are a wildcard here. Kevin Durant is one of few current players to beat LeBron in the finals over the past 5 years and he's looking like an MVP too. Unfortunately, the Nets team are not a well made team, and rookie coach Steve Nash may be in over his head come playoff time. Giannis is the reigning MVP too, and he looks like he's saving himself for the playoffs. I'd give him a slight nod here too. Finally, the Clippers while having a great team and arguably the second best player in the league (Kawhi) they also haven't shown they have the guts to beat the Lakers. However, I don't like betting against Kawhi given his record of success and I'd be likely to change my mind on this post All Star break.

A forecast of who wins the 2021 NBA championship would need to take into account a few factors: - COVID-19 - the prevalence of and the level of vaccine uptake by stakeholders. - Injuries - due to how NBA championship teams being structured with 'super stars' i.e. Lebron, KD, AD, Giannis, Kyrie, Harden, PG, Kwahi there are very significant 'key person risks' that exist. So an injury to anyone of these players will significantly diminish the team's probabilities for winning the 2021 championship

I like what @Rad4Caster did with his approach. However, I think that due to COVID and potentially players missing playoff games with contract tracing, there is a little more uncertainty and variability, which favors underdogs. Plus, Sportsbooks often take a VIG, so the implied percentages by the sportsbooks are a little inflated. Lastly, I think that there has to be a >0% that the season gets canceled, which @Rad4Caster does, but some other people do not.

Lakers are fairly clear favorites at this point in the season, at least according to https://www.oddsshark.com/nba/championship-odds, which appears to do a decent job of compiling odds from a bunch of bookmakers (and if you really want good data on sports, use bookmakers, who stand to gain (or lose) boatloads of money if they're right (or wrong)). Repeats seem at first to be fairly uncommon in the NBA, but they've happened four times in the last 20 years, with one of those being a three-peat...so 5 out of 20 years we've had a repeat winner. 25% chances aren't bad. Oh, and one of those was the Heat, with Lebron on board.

Via negativa: going back to 1995 only three times the underdogs have won in the finals: Pistons 2004, Mavericks 2011 and Toronto 2019, so one must take into account 25 : 3 = 12 % these outliers. Plus Tendency to form superteams in the NBA got higher, so more bifurcated title chances. Nevertheless one needs to assign at least 12 % chance to an underdog becoming champions. This year this tendeny is I believe twice as high, since the quality of excellent teams "who can get lucky on a championship run" is high with 6 teams, so twice the chance this season than in earlier decades. Utah (strong start) Golden State, Dallas, Philly, Bucks and Boston each 4 %, since all of them can make the road to the finals. Brooklyn and Lakers are more or less a coinflip at this time of evaluation 100 % - 24 % = 76 % among the high caliber teams. LAC half as likely to win versus LAL or Brooklyn therefore Brooklyn & Laker each 32 % and Clippers 12 %. Updates will be made with regard to the following upcoming facts. Injuries, Trades, Homecourt Advantage, not making the playoffs at the end of regular season, team chemistry, team mindset etc.
